# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: entity-framework
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:entity-framework/ef-core] Access to this page requires authorization.
[src:entity-framework/ef-core] You can try signing in or changing directories.
[src:entity-framework/ef-core] Entity Framework (EF) Core is a lightweight, extensible, open source and cross-platform version of the popular Entity Framework data access technology.
[src:entity-framework/ef-core] EF Core supports many database engines, see Database Providers for details.
[src:entity-framework/ef-core] With EF Core, data access is performed using a model.
[src:entity-framework/ef-core] A model is made up of entity classes and a context object that represents a session with the database.
[src:entity-framework/ef-core] The context object allows querying and saving data.
[src:entity-framework/ef-core] For more information, see Creating a Model.
[src:entity-framework/ef-core] Instances of your entity classes are retrieved from the database using Language Integrated Query (LINQ).
[src:entity-framework/ef-core] For more information, see Querying Data.
[src:entity-framework/ef-core] Data is created, deleted, and modified in the database using instances of your entity classes.
[src:entity-framework/ef-core] For introductory tutorials, see Getting Started with Entity Framework Core.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] Entity Framework 6.4 was the latest release of the classic framework.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] Although Entity Framework 6 is still supported, it is no longer being developed and will only receive fixes for security issues.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] A new framework known as Entity Framework Core (EF Core) was introduced in 2016 with similar but not complete feature parity.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] Version numbering of this framework restarted from 1.0.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] The Entity Framework is a set of technologies in ADO.NET that supports the development of data-oriented software applications.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] Architects and developers of data-oriented applications have typically struggled with the need to achieve two very different objectives.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] They must model the entities, relationships, and logic of the business problems they are solving, and they must also work with the data engines used to store and retrieve the data.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] The data can span multiple storage systems, each with its own protocols; even applications that work with a single storage system must balance the requirements of the storage system against the requirements of writing efficient and maintainable application code.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] This problem is generally referred to as the "object–relational impedance mismatch".
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] With an ORM, developers can work at a higher level of abstraction when they deal with data, and can create and maintain data-oriented applications with less code than in traditional applications.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] Entity Framework is the ORM solution currently promoted for use within the Microsoft development stack.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] The first version of Entity Framework (EFv1) was included with .NET Framework 3.5 Service Pack 1 and Visual Studio 2008 Service Pack 1, released on 11 August 2008 (2008-08-11).
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] This version was widely criticized, even attracting a 'vote of no confidence' signed by at least one thousand developers.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] The second version of Entity Framework, named Entity Framework 4.0 (EFv4), was released as part of .NET 4.0 on 12 April 2010 and addressed many of the criticisms made of version 1.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] A third version of Entity Framework, version 4.1, was released on April 12, 2011, with Code First support.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] A refresh of version 4.1, named Entity Framework 4.1 Update 1, was released on July 25, 2011.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] It includes bug fixes and new supported types.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] Version 4.3.1 was released on February 29, 2012.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] There were a few updates, like support for migration.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] Version 5.0.0 was released on August 11, 2012 and is targeted at .NET framework 4.5.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] Also, this version is available for .Net framework 4, but without any runtime advantages over version 4.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] Version 6.0 was released on October 17, 2013 and is now an open source project licensed under Apache License v2.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] Like ASP.NET MVC, its source code is hosted at GitHub using Git.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] This version has a number of improvements for code-first support.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] Microsoft then decided to modernize, componentize and bring .NET cross-platform to Linux, OSX and elsewhere, meaning the next version of Entity Framework would be a complete rewrite.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] On 27 June 2016, this was released as Entity Framework Core 1.0, alongside ASP.NET Core 1.0 and .NET Core 1.0.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] It was originally named Entity Framework 7, but was renamed to highlight that it was a complete rewrite rather than an incremental upgrade and it doesn't replace EF6.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] Entity Framework Core 1.0 is licensed under Apache License v2, and was built entirely in the open on GitHub.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] Entity Framework Core 3.1 (EF Core 3.1) was formally released for production use on 3 December 2019 (2019-12-03) and will be the preferred long-term supported version until at least 3 December 2022.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] Entity Framework Core 5.0 (EF Core 5) was released for production use on 9 November 2020 (2020-11-09).
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] It was retired and out of support 1.5 years later on May 10, 2022.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] Entity Framework Core 6.0 (EF Core 6) was released on 10 November 2021 (2021-11-10) and will be the preferred long-term supported version until at least 12 November 2024.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] Entity Framework Core 7.0 (EF Core 7) was released on 8 November 2022 (2022-11-08) adding features such as JSON columns and bulk updates.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] Entity Framework Core 8.0 (EF Core 8) was released on 14 November 2023 (2023-11-14) adding features such as Value objects using Complex Types and Primitive collections.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] The **Entity Data Model** (**EDM**) specifies the conceptual model (CSDL) of the data, using a modelling technique that is itself called Entity Data Model, an extended version of the *entity–relationship model*.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] The data model primarily describes the *Entities* and the *Associations* they participate in.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] The EDM schema is expressed in the *Schema Definition Language* (SDL), which is an application of XML (Extended markup language).
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] In addition, the mapping (MSL) of the elements of the conceptual schema (CSDL) to the storage schema (SSDL) must also be specified.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] The mapping specification is also expressed in XML.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] Visual Studio also provides the *Entity Designer* for visual creation of the EDM and the mapping specification.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] This approach is named as "Model First" approach, as alternatives to "Code First" and "Database First" approaches.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] The output of the tool is the XML file (*.edmx) specifying the schema and the mapping.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] Edmx file contains EF metadata artifacts (CSDL/MSL/SSDL content).
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] These three files (csdl, msl, ssdl) can also be created or edited by hand.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] The "Model First" approach is not going to be supported in EF Core version.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] Entity Data Model Wizard in Visual Studio initially generates a one-to-one (1:1) mapping between the database schema and the conceptual schema in most of the cases.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] In the relational schema, the elements are composed of the tables, with the primary and foreign keys gluing the related tables together.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] In contrast, the *Entity Types* define the conceptual schema of the data.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] The entity types are an aggregation of multiple typed fields – each field maps to a certain column in the database – and can contain information from multiple physical tables.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] The entity types can be related to each other, independent of the relationships in the physical schema.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] Entity Types form the class of objects entities conform to, with the Entities being instances of the entity types.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] Entities represent individual objects that form a part of the problem being solved by the application and are indexed by a key.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] The logical schema and its mapping with the physical schema is represented as an **Entity Data Model** (EDM), specified as an XML file.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] ADO.NET Entity Framework uses the EDM to actually perform the mapping letting the application work with the entities, while internally abstracting the use of ADO.NET constructs like *DataSet* and *RecordSet*.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] ADO.NET Entity Framework performs the *joins* necessary to have entity reference information from multiple tables, or when a relationship is traversed.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] When an entity is updated, it traces back which table the information came from and issues SQL update statements to update the tables in which some data has been updated.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] ADO.NET Entity Framework uses eSQL, a derivative of SQL, to perform queries, set-theoretic operations, and updates on entities and their relationships.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] Queries in eSQL, if required, are then translated to the native SQL flavor of the underlying database.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] Entity types and entity sets just form the logical EDM schema, and can be exposed as anything.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] ADO.NET Entity Framework includes *Object Service* that presents these entities as *Objects* with the elements and relationships exposed as properties.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] Thus Entity objects are just front-end to the instances of the EDM entity types, which lets Object Oriented languages access and use them.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] Similarly, other front-ends can be created, which expose the entities via web services (e.g., WCF Data Services) or XML that is used when entities are serialized for persistence storage or over-the-wire transfer.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] Entities are instances of *EntityType*s; they represent the individual instances of the objects (such as *customer*, *orders*) to which the information pertains.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] The identity of an entity is defined by the entity type it is an instance of; in that sense an entity type defines the class an entity belongs to and defines what *properties* an entity will have.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] Properties describe some aspect of the entity by giving it a name and a type.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] The properties of an entity type in ADO.NET Entity Framework are fully typed, and are fully compatible with the type system used in a DBMS system, as well as the Common Type System of the .NET Framework.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] A property can be *SimpleType*, or *ComplexType*, and can be multi-valued as well.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] All *EntityType*s belong to some namespace, and have an *EntityKey* property that uniquely identifies each instance of the entity type.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] All entity instances are housed in EntityContainers, which are per-project containers for entities.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] Each project has one or more named EntityContainers, which can reference entities across multiple namespaces and entity types.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] Multiple instances of one entity type can be stored in collections called EntitySets.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] One entity type can have multiple EntitySets.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] Any two entity types can be related, by either an *Association* relation or a *Containment* relation.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] For example, a shipment *is billed* to a customer is an association whereas an order *contains* order details is a containment relation.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] A containment relation can also be used to model inheritance between entities.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] The relation between two entity types is specified by a *Relationship Type*, instances of which, called *Relationships*, relate entity instances.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] In future releases, other kinds of relationship types such as *Composition*, or *Identification*, may be introduced.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] Relationship types are characterized by their degree (arity) or the count of entity types they relate and their multiplicity.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] However, in the initial release of ADO.NET Entity Framework, relationships are limited to a binary (of degree two) bi-directional relationship.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] Multiplicity defines how many entity instances can be related together.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] Based on multiplicity, relationships can be either one-to-one, one-to-many, or many-to-many.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] Relationships between entities are named; the name is called a Role.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] It defines the purpose of the relationship.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] A relationship type can also have an *Operation* or *Action* associated with it, which allows some action to be performed on an entity in the event of an action being performed on a related entity.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] A relationship can be specified to take an *Action* when some *Operation* is done on a related entity.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] For association relationships, which can have different semantics at either ends, different actions can be specified for either end.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] ADO.NET Entity Framework uses an XML based Data Definition Language called *Schema Definition Language* (SDL) to define the EDM Schema.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] The SDL defines the SimpleTypes similar to the CTS primitive types, including *String*, *Int32*, *Double*, *Decimal*, *Guid*, and *DateTime*, among others.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] An *Enumeration*, which defines a map of primitive values and names, is also considered a simple type.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] Enumerations are supported from framework version 5.0 onwards only.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] ComplexTypes are created from an aggregation of other types.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] A collection of properties of these types define an Entity Type.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] A relationship type is defined as specifying the end points and their multiplicities.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] ADO.NET Entity Framework uses a variant of the Structured Query Language, named *Entity SQL*, which is aimed at writing declarative queries and updates over entities and entity relationships – at the conceptual level.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] It differs from SQL in that it does not have explicit constructs for *joins* because the EDM is designed to abstract partitioning data across tables.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] Querying against the conceptual model is facilitated by *EntityClient* classes, which accepts an Entity SQL query.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] The query pipeline parses the Entity SQL query into a command tree, segregating the query across multiple tables, which is handed over to the EntityClient provider.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] Like ADO.NET data providers, an EntityClient provider is also initialized using a *Connection* object, which in addition to the usual parameters of data store and authentication info, requires the SDL schema and the mapping information.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] The EntityClient provider in turn then turns the Entity SQL command tree into an SQL query in the native flavor of the database.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] The execution of the query then returns an Entity SQL ResultSet, which is not limited to a tabular structure, unlike ADO.NET ResultSets.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] Canonical functions are supported by all Entity Framework-compliant data providers.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] They can be used in an Entity SQL query.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] Also, most of the extension methods in LINQ to Entities are translated to canonical functions.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] They are independent of any specific database.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] When ADO.NET data provider receives a function, it translates it to the desired SQL statement.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] But not all DBMSs have equivalent functionality and a set of standard embedded functions.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] There are also differences in the accuracy of calculations.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] Therefore, not all canonical functions are supported for all databases, and not all canonical functions return the same results.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] The LINQ to Entities provider allows Language Integrated Query (LINQ) to be used for querying data through the Entity Framework conceptual model.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] Developers can write queries in C# or Visual Basic using standard LINQ operators such as `Where`, `Select`, and `GroupBy`, rather than writing database-specific SQL statements.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] LINQ to Entities translates these queries into Entity Framework command trees, which are then converted into commands for the underlying database provider and executed against the data source.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] Because queries must be translated into database operations, not all LINQ operators and expressions are supported.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] Several database-specific providers with Entity Framework support are available.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] In the Entity Framework v4 new methods *ExecuteStoreQuery()* and *ExecuteStoreCommand()* were added to the class ObjectContext.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] Visual Studio has a feature called Visualizer.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] A LINQ query written in Visual Studio can be viewed as Native SQL using a Visualizer during debug session.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] A Visualizer for LINQ to Entities (Object Query) targeting all RDBMS is available in the Visual Studio Marketplace.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] Various profilers are commercially available to troubleshoot performance issues using Entity Framework, both for EF and EF Core variants.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] Entity Framework Core Tools and Extensions are available to enhance the performance of Entity Framework Core.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] EF Core exposes design-time commands for migrations and reverse engineering via the .NET CLI (dotnet ef) and Visual Studio Package Manager Console, which scaffold a DbContext and entity types from an existing database.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] Similar capabilities are available in other IDEs (e.g., Rider’s UI for EF Core commands), and advanced scenarios can leverage customizable scaffolding templates to control generated code.
[src:entity-framework/entity-framework] Entity Framework Tools and Extensions are available to enhance the performance of Entity Framework.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] LINQ extends the language by the addition of query expressions, which are akin to SQL statements, and can be used to conveniently extract and process data from arrays, enumerable classes, XML documents, relational databases, and third-party data sources.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] Other uses, which utilize query expressions as a general framework for readably composing arbitrary computations, include the construction of event handlers or monadic parsers.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] In what follows, the descriptions of the operators are based on the application of working with collections.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] Many of the operators take other functions as arguments.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] These functions may be supplied in the form of a named method or anonymous function.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] The set of query operators defined by LINQ is exposed to the user as the Standard Query Operator (SQO) application programming interface (API).
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] The `Select` operator performs a projection on the collection to select interesting aspects of the elements.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] The user supplies an arbitrary function, in the form of a named or lambda expression, which projects the data members.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] The function is passed to the operator as a delegate.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] This implements the Map higher-order function.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] The `Where` operator allows the definition of a set of predicate rules that are evaluated for each object in the collection, while objects that do not match the rule are filtered away.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] The predicate is supplied to the operator as a delegate.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] This implements the Filter higher-order function.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] For a user-provided mapping from collection elements to collections, semantically two steps are performed.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] First, every element is mapped to its corresponding collection.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] Second, the result of the first step is flattened by one level.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] `Select` and `Where` are both implementable in terms of `SelectMany`, as long as singleton and empty collections are available.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] The translation rules mentioned above still make it mandatory for a LINQ provider to provide the other two operators.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] This implements the Bind higher-order function.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] These operators optionally take a function that retrieves a certain numeric value from each element in the collection and uses it to find the sum, minimum, maximum or average values of all the elements in the collection, respectively.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] Overloaded versions take no function and act as if the identity is given as the lambda.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] This operator takes a function that specifies how two values are combined to form an intermediate or the final result.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] Optionally, a starting value can be supplied, enabling the result type of the aggregation to be arbitrary.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] Furthermore, a finalization function, taking the aggregation result to yet another value, can be supplied.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] This implements the Fold higher-order function.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] The `Join` operator performs an inner join on two collections, based on matching keys for objects in each collection.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] It takes two functions as delegates, one for each collection, that it executes on each object in the collection to extract the key from the object.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] It also takes another delegate in which the user specifies which data elements, from the two matched elements, should be used to create the resultant object.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] The `GroupJoin` operator performs a group join.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] Like the `Select` operator, the results of a join are instantiations of a different class, with all the data members of both the types of the source objects, or a subset of them.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] The `Take` operator selects the first `n` objects from a collection, while the `TakeWhile` operator, which takes a predicate, selects those objects that match the predicate (stopping at the first object that doesn't match it).
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] The `Skip` and `SkipWhile` operators are complements of `Take` and `TakeWhile` - they skip the first `n` objects from a collection, or those objects that match a predicate (for the case of `SkipWhile`).
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] The `OfType` operator is used to select the elements of a certain type.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] The `Concat` operator concatenates two collections.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] The `OrderBy` operator is used to specify the primary sort ordering of the elements in a collection according to some key.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] The default ordering is in ascending order, to reverse the order, the `OrderByDescending` operator is to be used.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] `ThenBy` and `ThenByDescending` specifies subsequent ordering of the elements.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] The function to extract the key value from the object is specified by the user as a delegate.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] The `Reverse` operator reverses a collection.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] The `GroupBy` operator takes a function that extracts a key value and returns a collection of `System.Linq.IGrouping<K, V>` objects, for each distinct key value.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] The `System.Linq.IGrouping<K, V>` objects can then be used to enumerate all the objects for a particular key value.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] The `Distinct` operator removes duplicate instances of an object from a collection.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] An overload of the operator takes an equality comparator object which defines the criteria for distinctness.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] These operators are used to perform a union, intersection and difference operation on two sequences, respectively.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] Each has an overload which takes an equality comparator object which defines the criteria for element equality.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] The `SequenceEqual` operator determines whether all elements in two collections are equal and in the same order.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] The `First` operator returns the first element for which the predicate yields true, or, if nothing matches, throws an exception.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] The `FirstOrDefault` operator is like the `First` operator except that it returns the default value for the element type (usually a null reference) in case nothing matches the predicate.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] The `Last` operator retrieves the last element to match the predicate, or throws an exception in case nothing matches.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] The `LastOrDefault` returns the default element value if nothing matches.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] The `Single` operator takes a predicate and returns the element that matches the predicate.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] An exception is thrown, if none or more than one element match the predicate.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] The `SingleOrDefault` operator takes a predicate and return the element that matches the predicate.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] If more than one element matches the predicate, an exception is thrown.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] If no element matches the predicate, a default value is returned.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] The `ElementAt` operator retrieves the element at a given index in the collection.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] The `Any` operator checks, if there are any elements in the collection matching the predicate.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] It does not select the element, but returns true if at least one element is matched.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] An invocation of any without a predicate returns true if the collection non-empty.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] The `All` operator returns true if all elements match the predicate.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] The `Contains` operator checks, if the collection contains a given element.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] The `Count` operator counts the number of elements in the given collection.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] An overload taking a predicate, counts the number of elements matching the predicate.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] While LINQ is mainly implemented as a library for .NET Framework 3.5, it also defines optional language extensions that make queries a first-class language construct and provide syntactic sugar for writing queries.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] These language extensions have initially been implemented in C# 3.0, VB 9.0, F# and Oxygene, with other languages like Nemerle having announced preliminary support.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] the types of variables `result`, `c` and `results` all are inferred by the compiler in accordance to the signatures of the methods eventually used.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] The C#3.0 specification defines a Query Expression Pattern along with translation rules from a LINQ expression to an expression in a subset of C# 3.0 without LINQ expressions.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] The translation thus defined is actually un-typed, which, in addition to lambda expressions being interpretable as either delegates or expression trees, allows for a great degree of flexibility for libraries wishing to expose parts of their interface as LINQ expression clauses.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] For example, **LINQ to Objects** works on `System.Collections.Generic.IEnumerable<T>`s and with delegates, whereas **LINQ to SQL** makes use of the expression trees.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] The expression trees are at the core of the LINQ extensibility mechanism, by which LINQ can be adapted for many data sources.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] The expression trees are handed over to LINQ Providers, which are data source-specific implementations that adapt the LINQ queries to be used with the data source.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] If they choose so, the LINQ Providers analyze the expression trees contained in a query in order to generate essential pieces needed for the execution of a query.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] This can be SQL fragments or any other completely different representation of code as further manipulatable data.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] LINQ comes with LINQ Providers for in-memory object collections, Microsoft SQL Server databases, ADO.NET datasets and XML documents.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] The LINQ to Objects provider is used for in-memory collections, using the local query execution engine of LINQ.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] The code generated by this provider refers to the implementation of the standard query operators as defined on the `Sequence` pattern and allows `System.Collections.Generic.IEnumerable<T>` collections to be queried locally.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] Current implementation of LINQ to Objects perform interface implementation checks to allow for fast membership tests, counts, and indexed lookup operations when they are supported by the runtime type of the `System.Collections.Generic.IEnumerable<T>`.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] The LINQ to XML provider converts an XML document to a collection of `System.Linq.Xml.XElement` objects, which are then queried against using the local execution engine that is provided as a part of the implementation of the standard query operator.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] The LINQ to SQL provider allows LINQ to be used to query Microsoft SQL Server databases, including SQL Server Compact databases.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] Since SQL Server data may reside on a remote server, and because SQL Server has its own query engine, LINQ to SQL does not use the query engine of LINQ.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] Instead, it converts a LINQ query to a SQL query that is then sent to SQL Server for processing.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] However, since SQL Server stores the data as relational data and LINQ works with data encapsulated in objects, the two representations must be mapped to one another.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] For this reason, LINQ to SQL also defines a mapping framework.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] The mapping is done by defining classes that correspond to the tables in the database, and containing all or a subset of the columns in the table as data members.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] The correspondence, along with other relational model attributes such as primary keys, are specified using LINQ to SQL-defined attributes.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] This class definition maps to a table named `Customers` and the two data members correspond to two columns.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] The classes must be defined before LINQ to SQL can be used.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] Visual Studio 2008 includes a mapping designer that can be used to create the mapping between the data schemas in the object as well as the relational domain.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] It can automatically create the corresponding classes from a database schema, as well as allow manual editing to create a different view by using only a subset of the tables or columns in a table.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] The mapping is implemented by the `System.Data.Linq.DataContext` that takes a connection string to the server, and can be used to generate a `System.Data.Linq.Table<T>` where `T` is the type to which the database table will be mapped.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] The `System.Data.Linq.Table<T>` encapsulates the data in the table, and implements the `System.Linq.IQueryable<T>` interface, so that the expression tree is created, which the LINQ to SQL provider handles.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] It converts the query into T-SQL and retrieves the result set from the database server.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] Since the processing happens at the database server, local methods, which are not defined as a part of the lambda expressions representing the predicates, cannot be used.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] However, it can use the stored procedures on the server.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] Any changes to the result set are tracked and can be submitted back to the database server.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] Since the LINQ to SQL provider (above) works only with Microsoft SQL Server databases, in order to support any generic database, LINQ also includes the LINQ to DataSets.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] It uses ADO.NET to handle the communication with the database.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] Once the data is in ADO.NET Datasets, LINQ to DataSets execute queries against these datasets.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] Non-professional users may struggle with subtleties in the **LINQ to Objects** features and syntax.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] Naive LINQ implementation patterns can lead to a catastrophic degradation of performance.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] Version 4 of the .NET framework includes Parallel Extensions for *Parallel LINQ* (PLINQ), a parallel execution engine for LINQ queries.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] It defines the `System.Linq.ParallelQuery<T>` class.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] Any implementation of the `System.Collections.Generic.IEnumerable<T>` interface can take advantage of the PLINQ engine by calling the `AsParallel<T>(this IEnumerable<T>)` extension method defined by the `System.Linq.ParallelEnumerable` class namespace of the .NET framework.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] The PLINQ engine can execute parts of a query concurrently on multiple threads, providing faster results.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] Many of the concepts that LINQ introduced were originally tested in Microsoft's **Cω** research project, formerly known by the codenames **X#** (X Sharp) and **Xen**.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] It was renamed to Cω after **Polyphonic C#** (another research language based on join calculus principles) was integrated into it.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] Cω attempts to make datastores (such as databases and XML documents) accessible with the same ease and type safety as traditional types like strings and arrays.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] Many of these ideas were inherited from an earlier incubation project within the WebData XML team called X# and Xen.
[src:entity-framework/language-integrated-query] Cω also includes new constructs to support concurrent programming; these features were largely derived from the earlier Polyphonic C# project.
[src:entity-framework/net] The **.NET** platform (pronounced as "*dot net"*; formerly named **.NET Core**) is a free and open-source, managed computer software framework for Windows, Linux, and macOS operating systems.
[src:entity-framework/net] It is a cross-platform successor to the .NET Framework.
[src:entity-framework/net] The project is mainly developed by Microsoft employees by way of the .NET Foundation and is today released under an MIT License.
[src:entity-framework/net] New versions of the .NET platform are released annually, typically in November.
[src:entity-framework/net] The most recent version of .NET is .NET 10, released in November 2025, which is a long-term support (LTS) version, and is scheduled to receive updates until November 2028.
[src:entity-framework/net] In the late 1990s, Microsoft began developing a managed code runtime and programming language (C#) which it billed together as part of the ".NET platform", with the core runtime and software libraries comprising the .NET Framework.
[src:entity-framework/net] Soon after the announcement of the C# language at the Professional Developers Conference in 2000 and previews of its software became available, Microsoft began a standardization effort through ECMA for what it dubbed the Common Language Infrastructure.
[src:entity-framework/net] The company continued development and support of its own implementation as proprietary, closed source software in the meantime.
[src:entity-framework/net] Miguel de Icaza describes .NET Core as a "redesigned version of .NET that is based on the simplified version of the class libraries", and Microsoft's Immo Landwerth explained that .NET Core would be "the foundation of all future .NET platforms".
[src:entity-framework/net] At the time of the announcement, the initial release of the .NET Core project had been seeded with a subset of the libraries' source code and coincided with the relicensing of Microsoft's existing .NET reference source away from the restrictions of the Ms-RSL.
[src:entity-framework/net] Landwerth acknowledged the disadvantages of the formerly selected shared license, explaining that it made codename Rotor "a non-starter" as a community-developed open source project because it did not meet the criteria of an Open Source Initiative (OSI) approved license.
[src:entity-framework/net] .NET Core 1.0 was released on June 27, 2016, along with Microsoft Visual Studio 2015 Update 3, which enables .NET Core development. .NET Core 1.0.4 and .NET Core 1.1.1 were released along with .NET Core Tools 1.0 and Visual Studio 2017 on March 7, 2017.
[src:entity-framework/net] .NET Core 2.0 was released on August 14, 2017, along with Visual Studio 2017 15.3, ASP.NET Core 2.0, and Entity Framework Core 2.0. .NET Core 2.1 was released on May 30, 2018.
[src:entity-framework/net] NET Core 2.2 was released on December 4, 2018.
[src:entity-framework/net] .NET Core 3 was released on September 23, 2019.
[src:entity-framework/net] NET Core 3 adds support for Windows desktop application development and significant performance improvements throughout the base library.
[src:entity-framework/net] In November 2020, Microsoft released .NET 5.0.
[src:entity-framework/net] The "Core" branding was abandoned and version 4.0 was skipped to avoid conflation with .NET Framework, of which the latest releases had all used 4.x versioning for all significant (non-bugfix) releases since 2010.
[src:entity-framework/net] .NET Core Runtime roughly uses semantic versioning, the *major.minor.patch* format.
[src:entity-framework/net] Major versions are incremented with "significant changes", API-breaking changes, or with the major version increase in an existing dependency.
[src:entity-framework/net] Minor versions are incremented with the addition of API features, dependencies, or with the minor version increase in an existing dependency.
[src:entity-framework/net] Patch versions are given for bug fixes, new platform support, or other changes not included above.
[src:entity-framework/net] As of 2019, runtime versions are backwards-compatible within the same major version number.
[src:entity-framework/net] For example, .NET Core 2.2 is able to run programs built for .NET Core 2.1.
[src:entity-framework/net] Runtime versions in the same minor version.
[src:entity-framework/net] This appears to have relaxed since .NET 5.
[src:entity-framework/net] A "roll-forward" behavior allows any .NET program to be run on any newer version given the correct settings.
[src:entity-framework/net] The SDK does not use semantic versioning.
[src:entity-framework/net] As of 2019, it supports targeting *every* runtime version prior to its maximum supported version.
[src:entity-framework/net] As of 2020, this extends down to .NET Framework runtimes as well, though downloading an additional "targeting pack" from NuGet may be necessary.
[src:entity-framework/net] The major and minor versions of an SDK always matches the major and minor versions of the runtime it contains or is aligned for.
[src:entity-framework/net] Alpine Linux, which primarily supports and uses musl libc, is supported since .NET Core 2.1.
[src:entity-framework/net] Windows Arm64 is natively supported since .NET 5.
[src:entity-framework/net] Previously, .NET on ARM meant applications compiled for the x86 architecture and run through the ARM emulation layer.
[src:entity-framework/net] Linux .NET runs on Power ISA to some extent since .NET 7, officially no support is claimed by Microsoft but .NET does contain code for Power ISA compatibility for Linux systems and is able to be compiled for Power ISA systems specifically 64 bit Little Endian variant.
[src:entity-framework/net] .NET fully supports C# and F# (and C++/CLI as of 3.1; only enabled on Windows) and supports Visual Basic .NET (for version 15.5 in .NET Core 5.0.100-preview.4, and some old versions supported in old .NET Core).
[src:entity-framework/net] VB.NET compiles and runs on .NET, but as of .NET Core 3.1, the separate Visual Basic Runtime is not implemented.
[src:entity-framework/net] Microsoft initially announced that .NET Core 3 would include the Visual Basic Runtime, but after two years the timeline for such support was updated to .NET 5.
[src:entity-framework/net] .NET supports the following cross-platform scenarios: ASP.NET Core web apps, command-line/console apps, libraries and Universal Windows Platform apps.
[src:entity-framework/net] Prior to .NET Core 3.0, it did not implement Windows Forms or Windows Presentation Foundation (WPF), which render the standard GUI for desktop software on Windows.
[src:entity-framework/net] However, from .NET Core 3 on, it started implementing them along with Universal Windows Platform (UWP).
[src:entity-framework/net] It was also possible to write cross-platform graphical applications using .NET with the GTK# language-binding for the GTK widget toolkit, but this binding has not been maintained for many years.
[src:entity-framework/net] Unlike .NET Framework, which is serviced using Windows Update, .NET used to rely on its package manager to receive updates.
[src:entity-framework/net] Since December 2020, however, .NET updates started being delivered via Windows Update as well.
[src:entity-framework/net] NuGet serves as the primary distribution mechanism for libraries and tools in the .NET ecosystem, including third-party components that extend core functionality.
[src:entity-framework/net] Among these are ADO.NET-compatible data providers, which offer database connectivity for systems beyond the default SQL Server support.
[src:entity-framework/net] These providers enable direct access to databases such as Oracle, MySQL, PostgreSQL, and others, and are commonly used in applications that require cross-platform data access, integration with ORM technologies, or support for specific database features.
[src:entity-framework/net] The two main components of .NET are CoreCLR and CoreFX, which are comparable to the Common Language Runtime (CLR) and the Framework Class Library (FCL) of the .NET Framework's Common Language Infrastructure (CLI) implementation.
[src:entity-framework/net] As an implementation of CLI's Standard Libraries, CoreFX shares a subset of .NET Framework APIs, however, it also comes with its own APIs that are not part of the .NET Framework.
[src:entity-framework/net] A variant of the .NET library is used for UWP.
[src:entity-framework/net] The .NET command-line interface offers an execution entry point for operating systems and provides developer services like compilation and package management.
[src:entity-framework/net] The official community mascot of .NET is the .NET Bot (stylized as "dotnet bot" or "dotnet-bot").
[src:entity-framework/net] The dotnet bot served as the placeholder developer for the initial check-in of the .NET source code when it was open-sourced.
[src:entity-framework/net] It has since been used as the official mascot.
[src:entity-framework/object-relational-mapping] In object-oriented programming, data-management tasks act on objects that combine scalar values into objects.
[src:entity-framework/object-relational-mapping] For example, consider an address book entry that represents a single person along with zero or more phone numbers and zero or more addresses.
[src:entity-framework/object-relational-mapping] This could be modeled in an object-oriented implementation by a "Person object" with an attribute/field to hold each data item that the entry comprises: the person's name, a list of phone numbers, and a list of addresses.
[src:entity-framework/object-relational-mapping] The list of phone numbers would itself contain "PhoneNumber objects" and so on.
[src:entity-framework/object-relational-mapping] Each such address-book entry is treated as a single object by the programming language (it can be referenced by a single variable containing a pointer to the object, for instance).
[src:entity-framework/object-relational-mapping] Various methods can be associated with the object, such as methods to return the preferred phone number, the home address, and so on.
[src:entity-framework/object-relational-mapping] By contrast, relational databases, such as SQL, group scalars into tuples, which are then enumerated in tables.
[src:entity-framework/object-relational-mapping] Tuples and objects have some general similarity, in that they are both ways to collect values into named fields such that the whole collection can be manipulated as a single compound entity.
[src:entity-framework/object-relational-mapping] They have many differences, though, in particular: lifecycle management (row insertion and deletion, versus garbage collection or reference counting), references to other entities (object references, versus foreign key references), and inheritance (non-existent in relational databases).
[src:entity-framework/object-relational-mapping] As well, objects are managed on-heap and are under full control of a single process, while database tuples are shared and must incorporate locking, merging, and retry.
[src:entity-framework/object-relational-mapping] Object–relational mapping provides automated support for mapping tuples to objects and back, while accounting for all of these differences.
[src:entity-framework/object-relational-mapping] The heart of the problem involves translating the logical representation of the objects into an atomized form that is capable of being stored in the database while preserving the properties of the objects and their relationships so that they can be reloaded as objects when needed.
[src:entity-framework/object-relational-mapping] If this storage and retrieval functionality is implemented, the objects are said to be persistent.
[src:entity-framework/object-relational-mapping] Implementation-specific details of storage drivers are generally wrapped in an API in the programming language in use, exposing methods to interact with the storage medium in a way which is simpler and more in line with the paradigms of surrounding code.
[src:entity-framework/object-relational-mapping] The following is a simple example, written in C# code, to execute a query written in SQL using a database engine.
[src:entity-framework/object-relational-mapping] In contrast, the following makes use of an ORM-job API which makes it possible to write code that naturally makes use of the features of the language.
[src:entity-framework/object-relational-mapping] The case above makes use of an object representing the storage repository and methods of that object.
[src:entity-framework/object-relational-mapping] Other frameworks might provide code as static methods, as in the example below, and yet other methods may not implement an object-oriented system at all.
[src:entity-framework/object-relational-mapping] Often the choice of paradigm is made for the best fit of the ORM into the surrounding language's design principles.
[src:entity-framework/object-relational-mapping] Compared to traditional techniques of exchange between an object-oriented language and a relational database, ORM often reduces the amount of code that needs to be written.
[src:entity-framework/object-relational-mapping] Disadvantages of ORM tools generally stem from the high level of abstraction obscuring what is actually happening in the implementation code.
[src:entity-framework/object-relational-mapping] Another approach is to use an object-oriented database management system (OODBMS) or document-oriented databases such as native XML databases that provide more flexibility in data modeling.
[src:entity-framework/object-relational-mapping] OODBMSs are databases designed specifically for working with object-oriented values.
[src:entity-framework/object-relational-mapping] Using an OODBMS eliminates the need for converting data to and from its SQL form, as the data is stored in its original object representation and relationships are directly represented, rather than requiring join tables/operations.
[src:entity-framework/object-relational-mapping] The equivalent of ORMs for document-oriented databases are called object-document mappers (ODMs).
[src:entity-framework/object-relational-mapping] Document-oriented databases also prevent the user from having to "shred" objects into table rows.
[src:entity-framework/object-relational-mapping] Many of these systems also support the XQuery query language to retrieve datasets.
[src:entity-framework/object-relational-mapping] Object-oriented databases tend to be used in complex, niche applications.
[src:entity-framework/object-relational-mapping] One of the arguments against using an OODBMS is that it may not be able to execute ad-hoc, application-independent queries.
[src:entity-framework/object-relational-mapping] For this reason, many programmers find themselves more at home with an object-SQL mapping system, even though most object-oriented databases are able to process SQL queries to a limited extent.
[src:entity-framework/object-relational-mapping] Other OODBMS provide replication to SQL databases, as a means of addressing the need for ad-hoc queries, while preserving well-known query patterns.
[src:entity-framework/object-relational-mapping] A variety of difficulties arise when considering how to match an object system to a relational database.
[src:entity-framework/object-relational-mapping] These difficulties are referred to as the object–relational impedance mismatch.
[src:entity-framework/object-relational-mapping] An alternative to implementing ORM is use of the native procedural languages provided with every major database.
[src:entity-framework/object-relational-mapping] These can be called from the client using SQL statements.
[src:entity-framework/object-relational-mapping] The Data Access Object (DAO) design pattern is used to abstract these statements and offer a lightweight object-oriented interface to the rest of the application.
[src:entity-framework/object-relational-mapping] ORMs are limited to their predefined functionality, which may not cover all edge cases or database features.
[src:entity-framework/object-relational-mapping] They usually mitigate this limitation by providing users with an interface to write raw queries, such as Django ORM.
